related_questions.question: What are the side effects of Himalayan tartary buckwheat?
related_questions.snippet: Other people can also become allergic to buckwheat. Re-exposure to buckwheat can lead to serious allergic reactions including skin rash; runny nose; asthma; and a potentially fatal drop in blood pressure, itching, swelling, and difficulty in breathing (anaphylactic shock).

related_questions.question: Where does Tartary buckwheat come from?
related_questions.snippet: Tartary buckwheat (Fagopyrum tataricum) is native to and was first cultivated in Central Asia. It's well adapted to cooler climates, thriving at higher altitudes, and has traditionally been grown in high-altitude areas of Nepal, Bhutan, southern China, and India.
